04124nam a22005055i 9780228000044DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280000447 a10.1515/97802280000442doi  a(DE-B1597)657790  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aP301.5.M48bF67 2019 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.442/992212231 aForth, Gregory, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Dog Pissing at the Edge of a Path :bAnimal Metaphors in an Eastern Indonesian Society /cGregory Forth. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b30 b&w photos, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tNote on Orthography -- tIntroductory Matters -- tMetaphors and “Metaphor” in Human-Animal Relations -- tDomestic Mammal Metaphors – and Some Wild Variants -- tMammals in Metaphor: Exclusively Wild Kinds -- tTalking with Birds -- tOther Non-Mammals in Metaphor: Snakes, Lizards, Fish, Frogs, and More -- tMetaphors with Bugs: Insects and Other Invertebrates -- tThe Differential Metaphorical Value of Different Animals -- tAnimal Metaphors in Social and Ontological Perspective -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Nage people of the eastern Indonesian island of Flores refer to someone who begins something but is regularly distracted by other matters as "a dog pissing at the edge of a path." In this first comprehensive study of animal metaphors in a non-Western society, Gregory Forth focuses on how the Nage understand metaphor and use their knowledge of animals to shape specific expressions. Based on extensive field research, A Dog Pissing at the Edge of a Path explores the meaning and use of over 560 animal metaphors employed by the Nage. Investigating how closely their indigenous concept of pata péle corresponds to the Greek-derived English concept of metaphor, Forth demonstrates that the Nage people understand these figures of speech in the same way as Westerners - namely as conventional ways of speaking about people and objects, not expressions of an essential identity between their animal vehicles and human referents. Theoretically engaging with anthropology's recent ontological turn, the book considers whether metaphors reveal significant differences in conceptions of human-animal relations, the human-animal contrast, and human understanding of other humans in different parts of the world. An incredible catalogue of animal-based linguistic art and Nage verbal conventions, A Dog Pissing at the Edge of a Path illuminates essential features of metaphorical thought everywhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnimalsxSocial aspectszIndonesiazFlores Island. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszIndonesiazFlores Island. 0aMetaphorxSocial aspectszIndonesiazFlores Island. 0aNage (Indonesian people)xEthnozoologyzIndonesiazFlores Island. 0aNage (Indonesian people)xSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228000044?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228000044423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228000044/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles